'''Rinkai-ji''' (臨海寺, りんかいじ) is a temple of the {{ill|Tōji Shingon Sect|ja|東寺真言宗|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Okinawa Prefecture|ja|沖縄県|12=draft}}, {{ill|Naha City|ja|那覇市|12=draft}}.
== History == [[File:琉球八景 臨海潮（湖）聲-Sound of the Lake at Rinkai (Rinkai kosei), from the series Eight Views of the Ryūkyū Islands (Ryūkyū hakkei) MET DP141125.jpg|thumb|200px|Rinkai Kosei (as depicted in a screen painting by {{ill|Katsushika Hokusai|ja|葛飾北斎|12=draft}}); a building along the embankment]] The date of its foundation is unknown. The temple is situated along an embankment leading to {{ill|Mie Castle|ja|三重城|12=draft}}, built in the mid-16th century, and once functioned as the bettō (administrative temple) of {{ill|Okimiya|ja|沖宮|12=draft}}. During the period of the {{ill|Ryukyu Kingdom|ja|琉球王国|12=draft}}, owing to its proximity to {{ill|Naha Port|ja|那覇港|12=draft}}, it served as a temporary lodging facility for foreigners.<ref name="観光">[https://www.naha-contentsdb.jp/spot/555]{{ill|Rinkai-ji|ja|臨海寺|12=draft}} Naha City "Naha City Tourism Resource Database"</ref>
After the separation of Shinto and Buddhism ({{ill|Shinbutsu Bunri|ja|神仏分離|12=draft}}) in the Meiji period, its traditional relationship with Okimiya was severed and the two followed independent paths. The temple suffered catastrophic damage during the {{ill|Battle of Okinawa|ja|沖縄戦|12=draft}} in 1945 (Showa 20) and was subsequently rebuilt at its current location in the postwar period.<ref name="観光"></ref>
== Access == * A 10‑minute walk from the {{ill|Toshibono Bus Stop|ja|天久停留所|12=draft}} (local bus).
== References == {{Footnotes}} {{Reflist}}
== Further Reading == * Okinawa Daihyakka Jiten, Vol.2: "Ke-To", edited by the Okinawa Daihyakka Jiten Publishing Office, Okinawa Times-sha, 1983
