'''Rinkai-ji''' (臨海寺, りんかいじ) is a temple of the {{ill|Tōji Shingon Sect|ja|東寺真言宗|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tōji Shingon Sect|qq=}} located in {{ill|Okinawa Prefecture|ja|沖縄県|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Okinawa Prefecture|qq=}}, {{ill|Naha City|ja|那覇市|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Naha City|qq=}}.
== History == [[File:琉球八景 臨海潮（湖）聲-Sound of the Lake at Rinkai (Rinkai kosei), from the series Eight Views of the Ryūkyū Islands (Ryūkyū hakkei) MET DP141125.jpg|thumb|200px|Rinkai Kosei (as depicted in a screen painting by {{ill|Katsushika Hokusai|ja|葛飾北斎|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Katsushika Hokusai|qq=}}); a building along the embankment]] The date of its foundation is unknown. The temple is situated along an embankment leading to {{ill|Mie Castle|ja|三重城|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mie Castle|qq=}}, built in the mid-16th century, and once functioned as the bettō (administrative temple) of {{ill|Okimiya|ja|沖宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Okimiya|qq=}}. During the period of the {{ill|Ryukyu Kingdom|ja|琉球王国|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ryukyu Kingdom|qq=}}, owing to its proximity to {{ill|Naha Port|ja|那覇港|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Naha Port|qq=}}, it served as a temporary lodging facility for foreigners.<ref name="観光">[https://www.naha-contentsdb.jp/spot/555]{{ill|Rinkai-ji|ja|臨海寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Rinkai-ji|qq=}} Naha City "Naha City Tourism Resource Database"</ref>
After the separation of Shinto and Buddhism ({{ill|Shinbutsu Bunri|ja|神仏分離|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinbutsu Bunri|qq=}}) in the Meiji period, its traditional relationship with Okimiya was severed and the two followed independent paths. The temple suffered catastrophic damage during the {{ill|Battle of Okinawa|ja|沖縄戦|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Battle of Okinawa|qq=}} in 1945 (Showa 20) and was subsequently rebuilt at its current location in the postwar period.<ref name="観光"></ref>
== Access == * A 10‑minute walk from the {{ill|Toshibono Bus Stop|ja|天久停留所|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toshibono Bus Stop|qq=}} (local bus).
== References == {{Footnotes}} {{Reflist}}
